            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "I'd like to pick this up, but I need a few pointers from the Nvim core team on how you want it to work.\n\nFor the URL paths I propose the following: `/doc/nightly/user/examplepage/` and `/doc/v0.11.5/user/examplepage/` where `/doc/user/examplepage/` redirects to `nightly`. Generally `latest` is used, but for Nvim it seems more appropriate to make the `nightly` docs the \"main\" ones (we could still alias the latest version to `latest`). Older versions are not indexed (`noindex`).\n\nVersions would be git-tag based. Currently we have a git tag for every semver patch release. For how many versions do we want to host the doc? Converting the Vimdoc to html is quite slow, so we either have (1) a longer running build job, (2) commit old docs to repo (as they won't change anyway), (3) cache them somewhere (GH actions?) or (4) limit the number of versions.\n\nMaybe we can start with each latest patch of each minor version starting from 0.9. Thus: `nightly`, `v0.9.5`, `v0.10.4`, and `v0.11.5`.\n\n- `gen_help_html.lua` might have trouble with flow layout for older doc pages. We could set `new_layout = {}` for older versions of the docs?",
