            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Thank you! My opinion:\n1. `nightly` is good since that aligns with how we name the release.\n2. our support policy is \"latest release plus tip of `master`\", so those are the only two versions we _need_ to care about (so `v0.11.5` and `nightly`; once 0.12 is out it'll be `v0.12` and `nightly`). As the latest version is always tagged as `stable`, you could simply use that?\n\nOf course, it wouldn't hurt to have more versions, out of historical interest if nothing else. But then I'd would simply push all tags that publish reasonably easily (without manual effort). I agree that committing the old docs to repo would be worth it then.\n\nActually, if conversion is expensive, I'd do that anyway for the release and only convert on-the-fly for the `nightly` branch. (This would imply two workflows: a release workflow that is triggered by a `v*` tag and commits the result, and a nightly workflow that is run on a cron and doesn't.)\n\nThis need not be part of the first implementation, though; for that, `stable` and `nightly` are the only important tags and can be re-generated on every run.",
